\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Physical and chemical energy storage in the abandoned offshore reservoirs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Ali A.
 Eftekhari
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The existing and in development offshore windmills in the North Sea will
 ensure the availability of abundant and cheap electricity in the region,
 yet fail to address the intermittent nature of the wind resources.
 The surplus electricity in the windy days and off peak time can be converted
 to physical (compressed and hot fluids) or chemical (synthetic fuels such
 as ammonia, methanol, or methane) forms and stored in the reservoirs.
 The stored energy is extracted and converted to electricity when there
 is a shortage of wind, or consumed as clean fuels for transportation.
 This project aims to study the feasibility of subsurface physical and chemical
 energy storage and extraction as an alternative for the abandonment of
 the North Sea oil and gas reservoirs.
 The feasibility and environmental impacts/benefits of the following energy
 storage processes will be investigated: green hydrogen, ammonia, methane,
 methanol, and compressed air.
 The main focus points of the project are the investigation and quantification
 of 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
1- the importance of subsurface energy storage for the future energy plans
 of Denmark.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
2- the required subsurface and topside criteria for the operation of the
 subsurface storage projects.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
3- the energy efficiency of different energy storage and extraction processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The report is organized in four chapters.
 In chapter 1, the electricity supply and demand of Denmark is analyzed
 and adjusted for the year 2050.
 The average surplus electricity is quantified and the time series data
 for both surplus and shortage of electricity is presented.
 Based on the presented data, the minimum efficiency requirement, the capacity
 of the synthetic fuel production processes, and the minimum subsurface
 volume requirement are quantified.
 In chapter 2 the energy efficiency of the production of different energy
 storage media is presented.
 In chapter 3, the energy efficiency of the subsurface energy storage and
 subsequent production is quantified using a mathematical model for the
 single phase single component compressible flow in porous media.
 Finally, in chapter 4 the main findings of this report and suggestions
 for future work are given.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
\begin_inset CommandInset toc
LatexCommand tableofcontents

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Problem definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:Problem-definition"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are exceeding scientific evidence for the role of anthropological
 carbon dioxide emission in an accelerated climate change, with potentially
 disastrous -although uncertain- aftermath.
 This has increased the societal pressure for a faster transition from hydrocarb
on-based to renewable-based energy.
 Besides these political and societal motivations, the declining conventional
 oil resources has reduced the efficiency of oil and gas recovery operations
 and increased the costs, leading eventually to the cessation of production
 and abandonment of the fields.
 The infrastructures, e.g.
 wells, platforms, topside equipment for transport and processing, and transport
 pipelines, even though still functional, will have to be removed as part
 of the abandonment operation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the same time, the renewable energy resources will grow in many areas
 of the world.
 In the North Sea region, several new windfarms are planned or under constructio
n, which will quadruple the capacity of renewable electricity production.
 This capacity that is several times more than the electricity demand in
 Denmark, is variable and intermittent and thus will not replace the reliable
 fossil-fuel power plants.
 The key factor in the transition to a fully renewable energy infrastructure
 is a large scale energy storage that can act as a buffer to provide a continuou
s power stream to the grids.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This project will investigate the feasibility of the alternative use of
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

to-be-abandoned
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 fields of the North Sea and their infrastructure as a large energy storage
 project that can address the intermittency of the wind energy in the North
 Sea region.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are three major questions that will be answered in this work.
 First, how much energy storage is needed in Denmark? Secondly, to what
 extent can the subsurface storage be helpful? Thirdly, what are the promising
 technologies from a technical point of view.
 This report will provide simple, reproducible, and realistic procedures
 and quantitative answers to these questions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Future energy need of Denmark
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denmark currently consumes around 100 kWh per person per day of energy in
 different forms.
 Eftekhari 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "eftekhari_quantifying_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 showed that this can be further categorized into a 30-30-40 category: 30%
 electricity, 30% heat, and 40% hydrocarbon fuel.
 Note that the hydrocarbon consumption for electricity production is not
 included in the 40% hydrocarbon fuel.
 We can assume that in the future, all the warming systems and short distance
 transport will be electrified; therefore, by assuming a realistic coefficient
 of performance for the future warming systems, the 30-30-40 can be roughly
 converted to 45-40, i.e.
 a demand of 45 kWh/day electricity per person and 40 kWh/day liquid fuel
 per person.
 This is the energy demand that I will use in the rest of this report.
 As for electricity production, the current plan is to quadruple the current
 electricity capacity of the wind mills in the North Sea.
 Since the capacity is not equal to the actual produced electricity (due
 to, e.g.
 technical problems, curtailment, weather conditions, etc.) I will estimate
 the intermittent electricity production of the windmills by quadrupling
 the current electricity production in Denmark.
 The data is available from Energinet.dk website and also as an electronic
 attachment to this report, including several Matlab functions for analysis
 and visualizations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Current-and-future"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows the electricity supply and demand for January 2020 (left) and January
 2050 (right).
 We can use the following equation to integrate the data and obtain the
 average energy supply and demand over different periods of time, i.e.
 from 24 hours to 6 month, as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:average-energy-demand"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{E}=\frac{1}{t_{2}-t_{1}}\int_{t_{1}}^{t_{2}}E\left(t\right)dt,\label{eq:average-energy-demand}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E(t)$
\end_inset

 [MW] is the electricity supply or demand in the future and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

 [s] and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset

 [s] represent a certain time period.
 The future energy supply and demand are estimated by using the correction
 factor extracted from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "eftekhari_quantifying_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, e.g.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{future}=\lambda_{i}E_{current},\quad i=s,\,d\label{eq:demand-adjust}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{d}=1.5$
\end_inset

 denotes a 50% in electricity demand and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{s}=4.0$
\end_inset

 denotes a 400% increase of windmill capacity in Denmark 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "noauthor_denmark_2020,noauthor_energy_2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note that this increase will be on the offshore sector only; however, here
 we assume that the overall wind energy capacity will increase by a factor
 of four.
 The other assumption in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:demand-adjust"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is that the weather (more specifically, wind) in 2050 will be similar
 to the weather condition in 2020.
 The visualized energy supply and demand in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Current-and-future"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows that periodically, the wind electricity supply is higher or lower
 than the electricity demand, creating electricity surplus and shortage,
 respectively.
 The alternation between surplus and shortage can occur within a few hours
 to few weeks.
 This is better visualized in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Average-electricity-supply"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 that shows the average surplus and shortage for periods of 24 hours to
 8 months.
 It can be observed that after around 6 months, the average surplus and
 shortage reach a constant value.
 This plot unveils three critical pieces of information about the wind electrici
ty supply and demand in 2050: first, the average shortage of electricity
 is 1.6 GW, which is a large amount of power and gives an indication of the
 amount of energy that needs to be stored (although sometimes the actual
 power shortage is temporarily higher as shown later).
 The good news is that the average electricity surplus is 2.25 GW, which
 is 620 MW higher than the average electricity shortage.
 These two numbers, however, serve as a constraint for the energy storage
 technology that is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta_{storage}>\frac{\text{Average shortage}}{\text{Average surplus}}=0.72,
\]

\end_inset

i.e.
 the efficiency of the storage technology must be higher than 72%.
\end_layout

