\begin_layout Standard
Although the previous analysis provides the average storage value, the real
 time electricity surplus that needs to be stored varies with time.
 The same occurs with the electricity shortage, i.e.
 the occasional electricity shortage can be much higher than its long-term
 average value.
 Both of these values are shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Electricity-surplus-smooth"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Any feasible storage process must be able to store a maximum power surplus
 of 5.0 to 10.0 GW (see the peaks of the curves in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Electricity-surplus-smooth"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

-left) and recuperate the stored power with a maximum rate of 3.0 to 6.0 GW
 (see the peaks of the curves in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Electricity-surplus-smooth"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

-right).
 These values are critical in the design of the storage and recuperation
 processes.
 The sizing of the required equipment and sub-processes will be discussed
 in the next sections.
 
\end_layout

