\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We end this section by estimating the subsurface volume that is required
 to store enough energy to cover for a eight month energy shortage.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Exergy-value-efficiency"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows the exergy per unit mole of different energy storage media that are
 studied in this report.
 Exergy, 
\begin_inset Formula $ex_{i}$
\end_inset

 [kJ/mol] is the amount of energy in a system that can be converted to mechanica
l work, i.e.
 movement or electricity.
 The maximum efficiency of producing each medium, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}$
\end_inset

, is also reported in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Exergy-value-efficiency"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 For these calculations, we need to have the density of the stored fluids
 at reservoir conditions, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{res}$
\end_inset

 [K] and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{res}$
\end_inset

 [bar].
 We used the typical reservoir conditions of the chalk fields in the Danish
 sector of the North Sea, i.e.
 70
\begin_inset Formula $^{o}$
\end_inset

C and 200 bar.
 The volume of the reservoir is calculated by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{res,i}=\frac{\bar{E}_{shortage}t_{storage}MW_{i}}{ex_{i}\rho_{i}\varphi},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{E}_{shortage}$
\end_inset

 [kW] is the average electricity shortage, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{shortage}$
\end_inset

 [s] is the period over which the electricity shortage is estimated (here
 8 months), 
\begin_inset Formula $MW_{i}$
\end_inset

 [kg/mol] is the molecular weight of the stored fluid, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

 [kg/m
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

] is the density of the stored fluid at reservoir condition, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 [-] is the porosity of the reservoir.
 Assuming a reservoir thickness of 100 m, the diameter of a chalk reservoir
 that can store the equivalent of eight-month electricity shortage in 2050
 is visualized in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Diameter-reservoir"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The diameter is calculated assuming an efficiency factor of one for all
 the energy conversions.
 A 2 to 3 times larger reservoir volume is required if all the efficiency
 factors are included in the computations.
 All in all, the required volume for the energy storage is only a small
 fraction of the available reservoir volumes in the North Sea.
 Therefore, the reservoir volume is not a bottleneck in the subsurface energy
 storage.
 A reservoir with a thickness of 100 m and a radius between 100 m to 3000
 m (considering the efficiency factors) can hold enough energy to compensate
 for 8 months of electricity shortage in Denmark in 2050.
 
\end_layout

