\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Diameter-reservoir"

\end_inset

Diameter of a 100 m thick chalk reservoir for the storage of fuel equivalent
 of 8-month electricity shortage in 2050.
 All the efficiency factors are assumed to be one.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the next chapter, several energy storage solutions will be discussed,
 and a thermodynamic model will be used to compare these solutions.
 The last chapter discusses the technical opportunities and limitations
 of each solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Chemical and physical energy storage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The oil and gas extraction from the Danish sector of the North Sea has been
 declining, which will lead to the cessation of production and abandonment
 (i.e., plugging of the wells and removal of the facilities).
 Simultaneously, the existing and in development offshore windmills in the
 North Sea will ensure the availability of abundant and cheap electricity
 in the region yet fail to address the intermittent nature of the wind resources.
 This chapter hypothesizes that the surplus electricity in the windy days
 and off-peak time can be converted to chemical energy (synthetic fuels,
 i.e.
 hydrogen, ammonia, methanol, or methane) forms and stored in the vast space
 of the abandoned oil and gas reservoirs under the North Sea.
 The stored energy can be extracted and consumed as carbon-neutral fuels
 for transportation or be converted back to electricity when there is a
 shortage of wind.
 This chapter studies the technical and thermodynamic feasibility of offshore
 conversion of electricity to chemical energy sources.
 The technical feasibility study deals with the sufficiency of the existing
 infrastructures including platforms, pipelines, and surface facilities
 to accommodate the process equipment for the conversion of electricity
 to chemical storable forms.
 Several processes including nitrogen and carbon dioxide separation from
 the atmosphere, electrolysis of seawater, and reduction of CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 and N
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 to synthetic fuels are simulated in Aspen Plus process simulator.
 The simulation results are used for the sizing of process equipment and
 the calculation of required platform area.
 The thermodynamic analysis quantifies the exergy loss during the conversion
 of electricity to fuel and back, and storage/extraction of chemical energy
 in the reservoirs based on the results of an in-house opensource dynamic
 model that simulates the multicomponent non-isothermal flow of fluids in
 the subsurface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Synthetic fuel storage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conversion of electricity to carbon-neutral fuels, known as power2x,
 p2x, e-refinery, and several other names, is a topic that is extensively
 studied.
 To produce a carbon-neutral fuel, the raw material for the production of
 the synthetic fuels must come from the nature, i.e.
 atmosphere and sea water, also known as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dead sate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the thermodynamic literature.
 The dead state refers to the average composition of the atmosphere, Earth's
 crust, and oceans that theoretically does not have any potential to do
 work.
 Here, we consider the production of hydrogen, ammonia, methane, and methanol.
 The raw material for the production of these fuels are air and seawater
 and the only driving force for the production processes is the surplus
 electricity from the windfarms.
 From the atmosphere, nitrogen and carbon dioxide need to be separated.
 From the seawater, hydrogen will be extracted via an electrolysis process.
 These processes are discussed in the next section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Atmospheric nitrogen and carbon dioxide
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Nitrogen
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nitrogen can be extracted from the air through the cryogenic distillation
 of air.
 In this process, shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Ammonia-synthesis-cryogenic"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, air is filtered, compressed, and liquefied by passing through a series
 of heat exchangers.
 The liquefied air then enters a high pressure followed by a low pressure
 distillation column.
 The separation of nitrogen from oxygen and other minor constituents of
 air is done based on the difference of their boiling points.
 Nitrogen is separated from the top side of the low pressure column.
 To liquefy air, a utility stream of around -200
\begin_inset Formula $^{o}$
\end_inset

C is required, that is often provided through the sudden expansion of a
 compressed refrigerant.
 Therefore, the process is energy intensive.
 Different values are reported in the literature for the electricity consumption
 per unit mole of separated nitrogen.
 These values depend on the heat integration of the process.
 The largest value reported in the literature is around 15 kJ/mol air distilled.
 In our simulation, we obtained a value of 32 kJ/mol, which is perhaps due
 to the poor heat integration in the simplified simulations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ammonia_cryogenic.jpg
	lyxscale 60
	width 14cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Ammonia-synthesis-cryogenic"

\end_inset

Ammonia synthesis process based on electrolysis and cryogenic air separation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Carbon dioxide
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Carbon dioxide is a stable molecule that exist in a small concentration
 of around 40 ppm (40
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

10
\begin_inset Formula $^{-6}$
\end_inset

 mole fraction) in the atmosphere.
 Theoretically, it can be separated from the atmosphere by spending an energy
 amount that is equal to the chemical exergy of carbon dioxide 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sankaranarayanan_efficiency_2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ex_{CO_{2}}=-RT_{00}\ln x_{CO_{2}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 [8.314 J/(mol.K)] is the universal gas constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{00}$
\end_inset

 [K] is the dead state temperature (15
\begin_inset Formula $^{o}$
\end_inset

C or 288.15 K in the North Sea region), and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{CO_{2}}$
\end_inset

 is the mole fraction of CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 in the atmosphere.
 This gives a value of 18744 J/mol, or roughly 20000 J/mol.
 Based on the previous experiences in the gas industry for the separation
 of low concentration acid gases such as CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

, SO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

, and H
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

S, the efficiency of such a process is quite low and rarely exceeds 5% 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "keith_why_2009,mahmoudkhani_low-energy_2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This means that the energy requirement for the separation of CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 from the atmosphere is around 400 kJ/mol or 9.0 MJ/kg CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In practice, this number is around 10 MJ/kg CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 which is both accurate and memorable, although larger numbers are reported
 for the state of the art technology 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "noauthor_direct_nodate"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Besides being energy-intensive, the separation of atmospheric CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 (also known as air capture) has a large footprint since a large mass transfer
 area is needed between the air and adsorbents/absorbents; the footprint
 of the eqipment is between 0.5 to 2 km
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

 for capturing 1 million ton of CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 per year 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "noauthor_direct_2021,mcqueen_cost_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This means that the direct air capture equipment cannot fit on a platform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are other ways of providing -close to- CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

-neutral carbon sources, e.g.
 from biomass.
 The captured CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 from the industrial point sources, e.g.
 steel and cement industries or fossil fuel power plant, if the capturing
 and conversion to fuel is performed in a close cycle can also be carbon-neutral.
 However, these two sources are available onshore and it is therefore easier
 to utilize them as close to the source as possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other source of carbon is the remaining oil and gas in the reservoirs,
 which can be extracted by, e.g.
 insitu combustion.
 However, this carbon source is not sustainable and we will not consider
 it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Fuels
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hydrogen
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent developments in the electrolysis technology has considerably increased
 the efficiency of hydrogen production from water.
 If the process is driven by the clean wind electricity, the produced hydrogen
 is a zero-emission fuel.
 Currently, hydrogen is included in all the energy scenarios for the countries
 in the North Sea region.
 For the offshore hydrogen production and storage, the following aspects
 need further investigations: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Fitting the water treatment, electrolysis, and compression equipment on
 a platform 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Pipeline integrity (for storage and gas transport) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Physico-bio-chemical interactions of hydrogen with the formation fluids
 and the chalk reservoir 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Capacity of reservoirs for storage of hydrogen and flow of hydrogen in the
 reservoir 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Energy efficiency and economic value of the process 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this research, the energy requirement of the process, the size of the
 process equipment, and the flow of hydrogen in the chalk reservoirs will
 be addressed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Green hydrogen production 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hydrogen can be produced from the electrolysis of water in the following
 reaction: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2H_{2}O→2H_{2}+O_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The minimum energy required for this reaction is given by the change of
 Gibbs free energy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rosen_energy_1995"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This reaction requires 39 kWh of electricity per kg hydrogen, but with
 the state of the art technology the value is closer to 48 kWh/kg 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gardner_hydrogen_2009,ozarslan_large-scale_2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hydrogen is purified by cooling it down to 308 K using cooling water.
 It removes the moisture from the hydrogen stream.
 The condensed water is recycled 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rosen_energy_1995"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Some extra moisture remains in the hydrogen stream, which will be removed
 later in the intercoolers between the compression stages 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rosen_energy_1995"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Electricity must be provided as direct current (DC), which introduces a
 loss of 2.5% for AC-DC conversion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rosen_energy_1995"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Rosen assumes an exergy efficiency of around 70% for the electrolysis of
 water for a mature electrolysis technology in 1995 (not considering other
 losses).
 He does not give more information on other steps of the process, e.g.
 water treatment and purification.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several technologies to produce hydrogen from water using electricity
 among which two are more mature and are available as commercial packages,
 viz.
 alkaline electrolysis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "brauns_alkaline_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and polymer electrolyte membrane cells (PEM) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "babic_critical_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 If the electricity is supplied by renewable resources, the produced hydrogen
 is called “green hydrogen” 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "granovskii_exergetic_2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 An efficiency of 60% to 70% is expected for these electrolysis processes,
 in which most of the energy loss is converted to heat.
 The energy loss during the compression of hydrogen will be calculated separatel
y in the following sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The storage of hydrogen in the subsurface is a relatively old topic 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ozarslan_large-scale_2012,zivar_underground_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Due to the high consumption of hydrogen, the petrochemical plants have
 been using salt caverns to store large volumes of hydrogen in the subsurface
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ozarslan_large-scale_2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Currently, the subsurface storage of green hydrogen is being studied by
 several investigators in different continents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As this report is being written, there are several green hydrogen production
 projects being announced.
 Ørsted has announced that as part of the project H2RES, supported by The
 Energy Technology Development and Demonstration Programme (EUDP) under
 the Danish Energy Agency, a hydrogen production unit with a 2 MW capacity
 will be built by the end of 2021 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "noauthor_orsted_nodate"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 that will produce up to 1000 kg/day of green hydrogen.
 These capacities, although an step forward, will not address the GW scale
 energy shortage that will certainly occur due to the intermittent nature
 of renewable electricity, as was discussed in Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Problem-definition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other issue that needs to be addressed here is the footprint of the
 electrolysis equipment.
 We saw in Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Problem-definition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 that the synthetic fuel production units are expected to consume several
 GW of surplus electricity.
 The main problem with these large amounts of power is that the electrolysis
 units are currently designed and built in MW scale.
 For example, one of the largest commercial PEM electrolysis units offered
 by NEL hydrogen has a capacity of 25 MW and requires 3 
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

 12 m
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

 area.
 Therefore, a 500 MW electrolysis plant that is made of 20 PEM cells is
 unlikely to to fit on a platform with other equipment although it is not
 impossible.
 A better option for the offshore hydrogen production is the installation
 of these electrolysis cells onboard a ship designed for this purpose.
 Otherwise, the onshore production of hydrogen seems to be the better option.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Last but not least is the conversion of the stored hydrogen to electricity.
 Currently, there is no gas turbine that can work with pure hydrogen as
 a fuel.
 Therefore, the produced hydrogen must be mixed with a hydrocarbon fuel
 such as methane.
 This will cause some carbon dioxide emission unless a carbon capture process
 is used, which will in turn reduce the efficiency of the process.
 Fitting a GW scale turbine on a platform is possible but similar to electrolysi
s cells highly unlikely for GW capacities
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As an example, Dan F host 6,800 tonnes of facilities and provides a power
 of 55 MW to the facilities.
 The highest point on the platform is 132 m above water.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 For example, a typical 25 MW turbine that is designed for offshore platforms
 and consumes a mixture of methane and hydrogen weighs approximately 250
 tonnes.
 Therefore, up to several hundred MW of gas turbine capacity can fit on
 a platform.
 But reaching to GW capacities can be a challenge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Methane
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Methanation process for the catalytic conversion of CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 and CO to methane was first suggested by Sendersen and Sabatier 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bolt_critical_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The reaction occurs in multiple steps starting with capturing of CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 or from an industrial or natural source or producing a mixture of CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 and CO by burning hydrocarbons (i.e.
 fossil fuels) or carbohydrates (i.e.
 biomass).
 In the presence of water vapor and at high temperatures, a considerable
 amount of CO and H
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 are also produced.
 H
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 can react with CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 and CO and convert them to methane.
 The reduction of CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 to methane by hydrogen is known as Sabatier reaction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bolt_critical_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
CO_{2}+4H_{2}\rightleftarrows CH_{4}+2H_{2}O\qquad\Delta H_{0}=-165\,\textrm{kJ/mol}.\label{eq:methane}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If the reactants, i.e.
 hydrogen and CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 are obtained from the dead state (i.e.
 seawater and atmosphere) using renewable electricity, the produced methane
 is carbon-neutral and sustainable.
 The reaction can be catalyzed by nickel or ruthenium and can be conducted
 in a packed bed reactor.
 The reaction rate in different ranges of pressure and temperature are reported
 in the literature.
 Although other reactions can occur at the high temperature and pressure
 of the methanations reactors, it is observed that the selectivity of the
 reaction towards methane is high 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "loder_reaction_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A selectivity of close to 100% is observed for catalytic methanation of
 CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 over nickel catalyst at a temperature close to 300
\begin_inset Formula $^{o}$
\end_inset

C.
 Although theoretically the reaction reaches 100% yield at room temperature,
 in practice the reaction rate is too small and the methane yield is zero.
 A temperature of at least 200
\begin_inset Formula $^{o}$
\end_inset

C is needed to get the catalytic reaction started.
 At temperatures above 500
\begin_inset Formula $^{o}$
\end_inset

C, the reaction goes backward, i.e.
 conversion of methane and water to hydrogen and CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This reaction is also known as methane reforming that is currently the
 main reaction for the production of the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

blue
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 hydrogen, i.e.
 hydrogen that is produced from a hydrocarbon.
 A schematic of the process for the production of green methane is shown
 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:methane-process"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 In this process, the required hydrogen and carbon dioxide are produced
 by the electrolysis of water and separation of atmospheric CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 The carbon source can also be provided from other alternative sources such
 as biomass or from the captured carbon dioxide from, e.g.
 cement or steel industries.
 However, capturing CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 from the atmosphere has the benefit of making the produced methane carbon-neutr
al or so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

green
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The reactor pressure is 20-70 bar 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "er-rbib_modelling_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and the temperature is between 473 to 673 K.
 The overall efficiency of the produced methane is calculated by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{methane}=ex_{CH_{4}}^{ch}\left(\frac{4ex_{H_{2}}^{ch}}{\eta_{electrolysis}}+\frac{ex_{CO_{2}}^{ch}}{\eta_{capture}}+\frac{ex_{compression}}{\eta_{comp}\eta_{driver}\eta_{transmission}}\right)^{-1},\label{eq:methane-efficiency}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $ex_{i}^{ch}$
\end_inset

 [kJ/mol] denotes the chemical exergy of component 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{j}$
\end_inset

 [-] shows the exergetic efficiency 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "eftekhari_exergy_2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 of the process 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $ex_{compression}$
\end_inset

 [kJ/mol methane] denotes the exergy requirement for the compression of
 hydrogen and CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 to the pressure of the methanation reactor in a multistage compressor.
 Since the reaction is exothermic, we assume that the heat of reaction is
 sufficient to heat up the reactor to the required temperature of 673 K.
 By calculating the compression energy using the method described in section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Compression-exergy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and replacing other efficiency factors from the previous sections, we obtain
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{methane}=36\%$
\end_inset

.
 This is much lower than the expected value of 72%.
 Moreover, since this process requires a large footprint for the direct
 atmospheric capture of CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 and electrolysis of water, we do not consider it as a feasible option that
 can address the intermittency of the wind energy in Denmark.
 It is worth mentioning that this process can easily fit on a platform and
 if both hydrogen and CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 are provided, e.g.
 via pipelines, operating this process on a platform is viable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename sabatier.gv.svg
	width 12cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:methane-process"

\end_inset

A block flow diagram of Sabatier process for the production of methane
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ammonia
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The block flow diagram of ammonia production is shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Haber-process"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Ammonia is produced by an exothermic catalytic reaction between nitrogen
 and hydrogen:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{2}+3H_{2}\rightarrow2NH_{3}.
\]

\end_inset

An ammonia reactor is operated at 200 bar and a temperature of 300 to 500
\begin_inset Formula $^{o}$
\end_inset

C 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "elnashaie_simulation_1988,morud_analysis_1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The raw material for the production of ammonia, i.e.
 nitrogen and hydrogen, can be obtained from the air and seawater by the
 cryogenic air separation and electrolysis units, respectively.
 The nitrogen and hydrogen feed streams are compressed to 150 to 250 bar
 and react in a packed bed reactor at 673 to 773 K.
 The reaction is exothermic and therefore does not require external heating;
 it also produces high temperature heat that can be used in the process.
 The process can fit on a platform even for large scale ammonia production.
 However, as discussed before, the electrolysis unit for GW scale production
 of hydrogen does not fit on the platform.
 The cryogenic separation of nitrogen from air can fit on the platform;
 however, having long and heavy distillation columns (i.e.
 60 theoretical trays) that work at very low temperatures on a platform
 can present several challenges for the stability of the platform and the
 extra room that is needed for the utilities.
 Therefore, we suggest an alternative design that is shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ammonia-new-design"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 In this new design, the separation of nitrogen from the atmosphere is done
 by a combustion reaction between the green hydrogen (produced in an electrolysi
s unit) and air in a gas turbine and later separating the mixture of steam
 and nitrogen by condensing the steam in a two phase separator.
 The separated nitrogen can either go to another Rankine cycle to produce
 some extra work or go to the ammonia reactor via a multistage compressor,
 where it reacts with compressed green hydrogen.
 The efficiency of the process is calculated by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta_{ammonia}=ex_{NH_{3}}^{ch}\left(\frac{\left(1.5+0.21/0.79\right)ex_{H_{2}}^{ch}}{\eta_{electrolysis}}+\frac{ex_{compression}}{\eta_{comp}\eta_{driver}\eta_{transmission}}-ex_{turbine}\right)^{-1},
\]

\end_inset

where the factor 0.21/0.79 indicates the number of moles of hydrogen that
 is consumed to burn oxygen for separating it from the nitrogen in the air.
 The efficiency of the new process for the production of ammonia is 43%
 which is lower but comparable to the 50% efficiency of the same process
 when nitrogen is separated in a cryogenic unit (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Ammonia-synthesis-cryogenic"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 It must be noted that currently there is no gas turbine that can operate
 on pure hydrogen and therefore the process can only be operational in the
 future.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ammonia has the highest synthesis energy efficiency among the considered
 fuels because of the lower energy demand of nitrogen separation and the
 fact that hydrogen directly reacts with nitrogen with no need for sacrificing
 extra molecules of hydrogen to remove the oxygen atoms as is the case when
 carbon dioxide is used as a reactant 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "elnashaie_simulation_1988"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename haber.gv.svg
	width 12cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Haber-process"

\end_inset

Haber process for the production of ammonia
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ammonia_new_design.jpg
	lyxscale 60
	width 14cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:ammonia-new-design"

\end_inset

A new design for offshore ammonia production
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Methanol
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Methanol can be synthesized from the catalytic reaction of hydrogen and
 carbon dioxide with the following reaction:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
CO_{2}+3H_{2}\rightarrow CH_{3}OH+H_{2}O\label{eq:methanol}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The reactor operates at 100 bar and 264
\begin_inset Formula $^{o}$
\end_inset

C 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "luyben_design_2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The reaction is exothermic and therefore the system is cooled down by circulati
ng water that produces steam.
 The material streams need to be compressed to 50 to 100 bar in the reactor.
 Compared to methane production in which two molecules of water is produced
 per molecule of methane, only one molecule of water is produced during
 the reduction of CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 to methanol.
 Therefore, even though the chemical exergy of methanol is lower than that
 of methane, the synthesis of methanol is slightly more efficient than the
 synthesis of methane.
 Similar to the methane and ammonia production, the efficiency of methanol
 synthesis is calculated by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta_{methanol}=ex_{CH_{3}OH}^{ch}\left(\frac{3ex_{H_{2}}^{ch}}{\eta_{electrolysis}}+\frac{ex_{CO_{2}}^{ch}}{\eta_{capture}}+\frac{ex_{compression}}{\eta_{comp}\eta_{driver}\eta_{transmission}}\right)^{-1},
\]

\end_inset

which is estimated to be 40%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The subsurface storage of methanol, however, is not advisable since methanol
 can be degraded by the subsurface microorganisms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sousa_deep-subsurface_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we did not include methanol in our subsurface model, although
 only the input component name need to be changed in the attached Matlab
 script to estimate the energy efficiency of the subsurface storage of methanol
 (excluding the microbial degradation reactions).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename methanol.gv.svg
	width 12cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A schematic of the methanol synthesis process
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Compressed air storage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compressed air storage is a relatively mature technology 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "stottlemyre_preliminary_1978"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the US, large tanks are used for the compression of air during the off-peak
 time to store cheap electricity in the form of high pressure air.
 The air is later used to drive a turbine and produce electricity during
 the peak time.
 This approach, although not energy efficient, is economical due to the
 special model of electricity pricing that encourages the consumers to shift
 their electricity demand to the off-peak hours.
 The large scale storage of electricity in the subsurface was first suggested
 as a method to reduce the waste energy of the large fossil fuel power plants.
 Many of the power plants are designed for a continuous operation and therefore
 their efficiency is significantly reduced if they operate under the design
 condition.
 It is not convenient to shut down the power plants when there is no consumer
 for the produced electricity because the start up is time consuming, expensive,
 and inefficient.
 Compressed air storage is one way of storing the surplus energy of a power
 plant that operates at its design condition.
 The large amount of stored energy can provide extra electricity during
 the peak time to balance the demand.
 The same idea can be used with the offshore windfarms, utilizing the abandoned
 gas fields as a storage space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:CA-schematic"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows an schematic of the compressed air energy storage that is also similar
 to any other gas storage processes.
 Air is injected in to the reservoir through a compressor.
 Since the input electricity to the process is variable, the efficiency
 of the injection compressor will vary since it does not always operate
 at its design condition.
 The injected air (or hydrogen, methane) is produced during the electricity
 shortage to flow through a gas turbine that rotates a generator and produces
 electricity.
 If all the friction losses in the reservoirs and in the well are ignored,
 the efficiency of this process can be as high as 50% (simply multiplying
 the efficiency of the compressor and the gas turbine).
 The efficiency drops in the dynamic operation due to the variable power
 input and also the friction and heat losses in the reservoir.
 This is discussed in the next chapter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename gas_storage_process.jpg
	lyxscale 50
	width 14cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:CA-schematic"

\end_inset

A block flow diagram of the subsurface gas storage process and the important
 efficiency factors
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Compression exergy
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Compression-exergy"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exergy of compressed air is calculated by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ex\left(T,p\right)=\left(H\left(T,p\right)-H\left(T_{00},p_{00}\right)\right)-T_{00}\left(S\left(T,p\right)-S_{00}\left(T_{00},p_{00}\right)\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{00}$
\end_inset

 [288.15 K] and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{00}$
\end_inset

 [101325 Pa] denote the dead state temperature and pressure, respectively;
 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 [kJ/mol] and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 [kJ/(mol.K)] denote the enthalpy and entropy, respectively that are calculated
 using the software CoolProp 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bell_coolprop_2013,bell_pure_2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The power consumption for the compression of air in a multi-stage compressor
 with interstage cooling is calculated in the following steps.
 First, the number of stages that is required to compress a gas stream from
 pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{in}$
\end_inset

 to pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{out}$
\end_inset

 is calculated by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{stage}=\frac{\ln\left(p_{out}/p_{in}\right)}{\ln r_{comp}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{comp}=p_{out}/p_{in}$
\end_inset

 is the compression ratio for each compressor.
 The number of compressors must be an integer number.
 Therefore, we choose the floor of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{stage}$
\end_inset

 as the number of compressors.
 We choose a compression ratio of 3.5 here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $p_{out}=r_{comp}p_{in}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the entropy 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{in}\left(p_{in},T_{in},x_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 and enthalpy 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{in}\left(p_{in},T_{in},x_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 of the input gas stream using the physical property package CoolProp.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the output temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{out}$
\end_inset

 [K] by solving the following nonlinear equation: 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{in}\left(p_{in},T_{in},x_{i}\right)-S_{out}\left(p_{out},T_{out},x_{i}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the enthalpy of the output -compressed- gas stream 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{out}\left(p_{out},T_{out},x_{i}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the isentropic compression (theoretical) work: 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{th}=H_{out}-H_{in}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The theoretical compression work can be converted to a practical value by
 considering the efficiency factor of the compressor, its electrical driver,
 and the efficiency factor for electricity transmission from the windmill,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{comp}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{driver}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{transmission}$
\end_inset

 respectively, i.e.,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{pr}=\frac{W_{th}}{\eta_{comp}\eta_{driver}\eta_{transmission}}.
\]

\end_inset

Typical values for these efficiency factors are shown in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Typical-values-etta"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tab:Typical-values-etta"

\end_inset

Typical values for the efficiency factors of compressors, electrical drivers,
 and power plants
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

