\begin_layout Chapter
Subsurface energy storage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although there are several reservoirs that can be used for the storage of
 energy, we can divide them into two main groups of sandstone reservoir
 (e.g.
 Harald West) and chalk reservoirs (e.g.
 Halfdan).
 Harald West is a sandstone gas reservoir at a depth of approximately 3500
 m and a temperature of 135
\begin_inset Formula $^{o}$
\end_inset

C.
 The porosity of the reservoir is 0.17 with a permeability of 1 to 50 mD
 in different layers.
 The thickness of the two high permeable layers (9 and 54 mD) is approximately
 100 m.
 The Halfdan chalk reservoir is 2000 m deep with an average porosity of
 0.31 and an average permeability of 3 mD.
 The wells in Harald West are vertical and the chalk fields are typically
 producing through long horizontal wells.
 In the case of a the vertical wells, we assume a thickness of 100 m for
 the reservoir, which means that a radius of 100 to 1000 m around the well
 will be utilized as the fuel storage space.
 For the longer horizontal wells, a smaller area around the well is required
 for the energy storage.
 We assume a well diameter of 5
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for all the energy storage and production wells.
 The geometry of the reservoir is shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:A-cylindrical-domain"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Problem formulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:A-cylindrical-domain"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows a gas reservoir represented as a cylindrical domain.
 The top and bottom of the reservoir are closed, i.e.
 no flow, and the outskirt of the domain can either be closed or at hydrostatic
 pressure.
 The top side of the reservoir is located at depth 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 [m], the thickness of the reservoir is 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{res}$
\end_inset

 [m] and the radius of the well and the reservoir are 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5D_{well}$
\end_inset

 [m] and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{res}$
\end_inset

 [m] respectively.
 The injection rate is calculated based on the surplus electricity and the
 efficiency factor of the synthetic fuel (or compressed air) production.
 The total injection velocity is calculated by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{inj}=\frac{E_{surpluss}\eta_{j}MW_{j}}{\pi D_{well}H_{res}ex_{j}^{ch}\rho_{j}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{j}$
\end_inset

 [kg/m
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

] is the density of the synthetic fuel 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and is calculated at the bottom hole pressure and injection temperature
 (that is assumed to be close to the reservoir temperature).
 The bottom hole pressure is unknown and is calculated by trial and error
 between the reservoir model and the injection boundary condition that is
 obtained from the above equation.
 For the compressed air, the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $ex_{j}^{ch}$
\end_inset

 [kJ/mol] that denotes the chemical exergy of the synthetic fuel 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is replaced by the physical exergy of the compressed air which is again
 a function of the bottom hole pressure and is calculated by trial and error.
 The compression work for the injection of the gaseous fluid is calculated
 for the injection pressure of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{inj}=p_{bh}+\Delta p_{pipe}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{bh}$
\end_inset

 [Pa] is the bottom hole pressure and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p_{pipe}$
\end_inset

 [Pa] is the pressure drop in the pipe that is calculated by the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pipe
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 unit in the software Aspen Plus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that for 2 months from 1st of October to 1st of December we only
 store the fluids in the subsurface (when surplus electricity is available)
 and after that storage period, depending on the electricity supply and
 demand we will have storage or production phases.
 The produced fluid from the reservoir is used for the supply of the electricity
 shortage; therefore, the withdrawal rate is determined by the electricity
 shortage.
 If the withdrawal rate is too high, the reservoir might not have enough
 driving force to produce the requested flow.
 In these situations, the bottom hole pressure becomes negative and the
 program produces an error.
 A better approach is to estimate the maximum productivity of the reservoir
 using an analytical solution 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hagoort_fundamentals_1988,al-hussainy_application_1966,al-hussainy_flow_1966"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This approach is not currently implemented.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename cylindrical_domain.svg
	width 8cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:A-cylindrical-domain"

\end_inset

A cylindrical domain for the simulation of synthetic fuel storage in the
 subsurface
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Subsurface storage model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the storage of the synthetic fuels and compressed air in the gas reservoirs,
 we use a single-phase multi-component flow formulation.
 The storage of gas in the water flooded reservoirs is not a good idea since
 most of the gas will be trapped by capillary forces, and therefore will
 be permanently stored.
 It is possible to dry out the reservoir and prepare it for the gas injection
 by, e.g.
 injection of superheated steam or hot gases.
 However, it will require large amounts of energy and can potentially create
 thermally-induced fractures in the reservoir.
 We will therefore consider only the gas reservoirs for the storage of gaseous
 phase energy careers.
 For the liquid phase, we will use both gas and oil reservoirs.
 In both cases, we will include the compressibility of the fluids in the
 model as it is a major contributing driving force in the extraction of
 the fluids from the reservoir.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The single phase compressible flow in porous media reads
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\left(\varphi\rho\right)+\nabla.\left(\rho\mathbf{u}\right)=0,\label{eq:continuity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the Darcy velocity (assuming single phase flow and negligible gravity
 effect) is described by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{u}=-\frac{k}{\mu}\nabla p,\label{eq:darcy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The flow of the synthetic fuel in the subsurface is described by the advection-d
iffusion equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\left(\varphi c\right)+\nabla\left(\mathbf{u}c-\varphi\mathcal{D}\nabla c\right)=0.\label{eq:adv-diff-single}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the above equations, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 [-] denotes porosity, 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 [m
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

] denotes permeability, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 [kg/m
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

] denotes the fluid density, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 [Pa] denotes the reservoir pressure, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 [Pa.s] denotes the fluid viscosity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 [m
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

/s] denotes the diffusivity of the synthetic fuel, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 [mol/m
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

] is the concentration of the synthetic fuel.
 Both viscosity and density are functions of the fuel concentration.
 As discussed before, the injection rate in the well is a function of the
 supplied electricity that is obtained by the real surplus electricity data
 of 2020 adjusted for 2050.
 The above equations are solved numerically with the finite volume method.
 We performed the discretizition in the free Matlab software package FVTool
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "eftekhari_fvtool_2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in a two-dimensional axisymmetric (i.e.
 cylindrical) coordinate.
 We used different permeability fields, including higher permeability near
 the wellbore region.
 A version with the possibility of adding fracture is also implemented.
 The permeability field that represents Harald West field with an stimulated
 near-well zone is shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Permeability-field"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename CA_perm_harald.jpg
	lyxscale 40
	width 14cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Permeability-field"

\end_inset

Permeability field for the simulation of compressed air and ammonia injection
 in the Harald West reservoir; the permeability in the near-well region
 is 100 times higher than the average permeability of the field.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results and discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we discuss the results of the compressed air storage and
 ammonia storage in the Harald West field.
 The permeability field is as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Permeability-field"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 A radius of 20 m around the well is stimulated to obtain a permeability
 100 times higher than the average permeability of the reservoir.
 This stimulation is necessary for the injection of the large flow rates
 that are required for the storage of energy in MW to GW scales.
 The withdrawal from the reservoir starts on 1st of December 2050 whenever
 there is an electricity shortage.
 The production rate is adjusted such that the bottom hole pressure is high
 enough, i.e.
 it can overcome the pressure drop in the well and also generate electricity
 in the gas turbine on the platform.
 The efficiency of the turbine is similar to the efficiency of the injection
 compressor and does not vary with the operating condition.
 We assume that 20 MW of the surplus electricity is directed to the compressed
 air storage unit in Harald West.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Compressed air
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Bottom-hole-pressure-CA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows the bottom hole pressure history.
 We use this pressure history to calculate the average values of the produced
 electricity divided by the consumed surplus electricity for the injection
 of air over the four months of operation from October to January 2050.
 The analysis of the result shows that only 1.6% of the total 20 MW of consumed
 electricity is reproduced in the compressed air storage process, which
 is not significant.
 Moreover, the pressure increase in the reservoir is several times higher
 than the hydrostatic pressure and is localized is a small area close to
 the injection well.
 This large average pressure increase combined with the fast pressure increase
 and drop (up to 1000 bar in few days or even hours) due to the fluctuation
 of the surplus wind electricity can lead to geomechanical instabilities
 in the reservoir.
 Therefore, it is recommended to store smaller fractions of the available
 surplus electricity through a single vertical well.
 The tracer profile, depicted in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Tracer-profile-CA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, shows that after 4 months of operation the tracer has only diffused to
 a radius of 700 m in the reservoir.
 This means that a more confined space of a salt cavern, which offers the
 same storage space but does not pose the problems of flow in a porous medium
 and can be a better storage medium if it can confine a compressed gas at
 several hundred bar.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename CA_p_hist.jpg
	lyxscale 60
	width 8cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Bottom-hole-pressure-CA"

\end_inset

Bottom hole pressure history after the injection of compressed air from
 October 2050 to 1st of December 2050 and storage and production onward.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename CA_tracer_harald.jpg
	lyxscale 50
	width 14cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Tracer-profile-CA"

\end_inset

Tracer profile after 4 months of injection and production of compressed
 air in the Harald West reservoir.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand the low energy recovery efficiency, we can consider the pressure
 profile shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Pressure-profile-CA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The pressure in the stimulated near well region drops relatively faster
 due to a high withdrawal rate.
 However, since the permeability of the reservoir is low, the flow from
 the first 100 m of the reservoir to the stimulated zone is a limiting factor
 even though the pressure in the reservoir is still high (more than 600
 bar).
 An analytical model can provide a better analysis tool for the compressed
 air energy storage by estimating the maximum injection and withdrawal rates.
 The necessary routine for the calculation of pseudo-pressure (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "al-hussainy_application_1966"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) is already written in the attached Matlab files and can be used for the
 analysis of the highest potential of a gas field for the compressed air
 energy storage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename CA_pressure_harald.jpg
	lyxscale 50
	width 14cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Pressure-profile-CA"

\end_inset

Pressure profile at the end of compressed air storage/production in Harald
 West
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ammonia
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous section, we saw that the storage of compressed air which
 has a limited exergy value (i.e.
 potential to do mechanical work) compared to synthetic fuels requires larger
 volumes and subsequently very high injection and withdrawal rates that
 leads to unrealistically large pressure gradients in the reservoir.
 This is a problem that can be addressed by the conversion and storage of
 energy in a medium with a higher exergy per unit volume such as ammonia.
 Here, we assume that 100 MW of the surplus electricity is provided to the
 ammonia production and storage unit in Harald West, which is 5 times higher
 than the electricity consumption in the compressed air storage unit.
 As can be seen in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Bottom-hole-pressure-NH3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the injection pressure in the reservoir is only 150 bar higher than the
 hydrostatic pressure and thus within a reasonable range.
 The pressure fluctuation is between 200 to 350 bar, which can create geomechani
cal failure in the reservoir and needs to be further investigated.
 Once again, the production rate is controlled by the low permeability of
 the reservoir as can be seen in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Pressure-profile-NH3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 To avoid a negative bottom hole pressure in the simulations, we imposed
 a withdrawal rate limit that is 20% of the maximum injection rate during
 the storage phase.
 With this limit, the efficiency of the electricity production (assuming
 an efficiency of 60% for the conversion of ammonia to electricity) from
 the stored ammonia is only 2.3%.
 This is higher than the efficiency of compressed air energy storage but
 does not provide the 72% efficiency that is required for a feasible storage
 solution that can address the intermittency of renewable electricity production
 in the North Sea windfarms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

